Indonesia Stocks: Adaro Energy, Bakrie Sumatera, Elnusa

-- B y   F e m i   A d i
-- 
2011-06-17T10:47:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-17/indonesia-stocks-chandra-asri-indomobil-sukses-kimia-farma.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  declined 18.17 points, or 0.5
percent to 3,722.30, set for the lowest close since Apr. 14.  Energy companies: PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),
Indonesia’s biggest listed oil company, slipped 4.1 percent to
2,325 rupiah. PT Elnusa (ELSA IJ), an oil services company,
tumbled 5.6 percent to 255 rupiah, set for the lowest close
since Apr. 14 2009. PT Adaro Energy (ADRO IJ), Indonesia’s
second-largest coal producer, slumped 3.2 percent to 2,275
rupiah, the steepest drop since May 12.  Oil dropped to its lowest in four months in  New York  on
concern the Greek debt crisis will threaten  Europe ’s economic
recovery, curbing fuel demand. Crude for July delivery on the
 New York Mercantile Exchange  slipped as much as $2.83 to $92.12
a barrel, the lowest since Feb. 22, and was at $93.44 at 10:55
a.m. London time. The price has lost 5.9 percent this week, its
biggest decline in six weeks.  Rubber producers: PT Bakrie Sumatera Plantations (UNSP IJ)
slipped 1.2 percent to 415 rupiah.  November-delivery rubber dropped as much as 2.1 percent to
375.5 yen a kilogram ($4,723 a metric ton), the lowest level
since May 24, before settling at 379.8 yen on the Tokyo
Commodity Exchange. The contract lost 1 percent this week.  PT Chandra Asri Petrochemical (TPIA IJ): The polypropylene
producer rose 5.1 percent to 4,100 rupiah. The company will
delay plans for a rights offer due to uncertain market
conditions, the company said in a statement published in
Investor Daily. The Indonesian company didn’t say for how long
the proposed June share offer would be delayed.  PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the nation’s second-
largest listed oil company, gained 2.6 percent to 194 rupiah.
The company plans to refinance as much as $200 million of debt
due in 2013, President Director Imam Agustino said in Jakarta
yesterday. Shareholders approved the plan to pledge assets for
the debt refinancing, Agustino said. Energi Mega’s stake in the
Kangean gas block in the eastern part of  Indonesia ’s Java island
is among the assets the company will pledge, he said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
